# Skill Router

Use this rule when a request should be routed to the best available skill, project rule, or workflow before work begins.

## Routing Workflow

1. Identify the task type: coding, debugging, UI/UX, prototype, Figma handoff, planning, review, verification, docs, or mixed.
2. Respect explicitly named rules or skills first.
3. Choose one primary workflow and at most two supporting workflows.
4. Do not load or apply every rule just because it exists.
5. If the right workflow is unavailable, proceed with normal Cursor behavior and state the assumption briefly.

## Routing Map

- General coding, implementation, refactoring: engineering workflow or `using-superpowers`.
- Test-first implementation: `test-driven-development`.
- Bugs, broken tests, runtime failures: `systematic-debugging`.
- Large ambiguous tasks: `writing-plans`, then `executing-plans`.
- Final checks: `verification-before-completion`.
- Code review: `requesting-code-review`.
- Applying review feedback: `receiving-code-review`.
- Conservative engineering judgment: `karpathy-guidelines`.
- Web/mobile UI, dashboards, components, accessibility, visual polish: `ui-ux-pro-max`.
- Narrow visual design: `design`, `design-system`, `ui-styling`, `brand`, `banner-design`, or `slides`.
- High-fidelity HTML prototypes, interactive demos, animation demos, design variants: `huashu-design`.
- Figma URLs or design-to-code: Figma workflow first.

## Communication

Before starting substantial work, state the selected workflow in one short sentence. Then execute the task.

